    \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def longestSemiRepetitiveSubstring(self, s: str) -> int:\n        if len(s) <= 1:\n            return len(s)\n        \n        max_length = 1\n        start = 0\n        first_pair_index = -1\n        \n        for end in range(1, len(s)):\n            if s[end] == s[end - 1]:\n                if first_pair_index != -1:\n                    start = first_pair_index + 1\n                first_pair_index = end - 1\n            max_length = max(max_length, end - start + 1)\n        \n        return max_length\n```\n\nThis solution uses a sliding window approach to find the longest semi-repetitive substring. It keeps track of the start of the current window and the index of the first pair of adjacent identical digits encountered. When a second pair is found, it adjusts the start of the window to be just after the first pair, ensuring that the substring remains semi-repetitive. The maximum length of such substrings is updated and returned.", "estimated_date": 1685836800000}